best_practices:
  _desc: "1. Use unknown over any: Enforce type checking. 2. Prefer interface for object shapes: Better error messages. 3. Use type for unions and complex types: More flexible. 4. Leverage type inference: Let TypeScript infer when possible. 5. Create helper types: Build reusable type utilities. 6. Use cons..."
type_testing:
  code[13]:
    - // Type assertion tests
    - "type AssertEqual<T, U> = [T] extends [U]"
    - "? [U] extends [T]"
    - ? true
    - ": false"
    - ": false;"
    - type Test1 = AssertEqual<string, string>; // true
    - type Test2 = AssertEqual<string, number>; // false
    - type Test3 = AssertEqual<string | number, string>; // false
    - // Expect error helper
    - type ExpectError<T extends never> = T;
    - // Example usage
    - type ShouldError = ExpectError<AssertEqual<string, number>>;
common_pitfalls:
  _desc: "1. Over-using any: Defeats the purpose of TypeScript. 2. Ignoring strict null checks: Can lead to runtime errors. 3. Too complex types: Can slow down compilation. 4. Not using discriminated unions: Misses type narrowing opportunities. 5. Forgetting readonly modifiers: Allows unintended mutations...."
performance_considerations:
  [5]: Avoid deeply nested conditional types,Use simple types when possible,Cache complex type computations,Limit recursion depth in recursive types,Use build tools to skip type checking in production
